Divide every training image into 16 smaller patches. Since the original images are with 2828 pixels, we need to divide the image into 7 7 patches. There is no overlap between those patches.Patches are ordered from the top left corner to the bottom right corner

RNN LSTM Model

Train your RNN in a way that it can predict the next patch out of the so-far observed patches.

In [123]:
# model = Sequential([
#           # Conv1D(filters=32, kernel_size=2, activation = 'relu', input_shape= (None,49)),
#           # MaxPool1D(pool_size=2, strides=2),
#           GRU(49,kernel_initializer=initializers.glorot_normal(),return_sequences=True, input_shape= (None,49)),
#           BatchNormalization(),
#           Dropout(0.8),
#           GRU(49,kernel_initializer=initializers.glorot_normal(),return_sequences=True),
#           BatchNormalization(),
#           Dropout(0.8),
#           GRU(49,kernel_initializer=initializers.glorot_normal(),return_sequences=True),
#           BatchNormalization(),
#           Dropout(0.8),
#           Dense(49,activation='tanh',kernel_initializer=initializers.glorot_normal())
# ])

input1 = layers.Input(shape=(None,49))
# Return states in addition to output
out1, h1, c1 = layers.LSTM(units= 32,activation='relu',return_sequences=True, return_state=True)(input1)
# We discard `outputs` and only keep the states.
states1 = [h1, c1]

# Pass the 2 states to a new LSTM layer, as initial state
out2, h2,c2 = layers.LSTM(units = 32,activation='relu',return_sequences=True, return_state=True)(out1, initial_state=states1)

final_output = layers.Dense(units = 49,activation='relu')(out2)

model = keras.Model(input1,final_output)
model.summary()


#Optimizer
opt = Adam(learning_rate=0.0001)
model.compile(loss=tf.keras.losses.BinaryCrossentropy(from_logits=True), metrics=['accuracy'],optimizer=opt)
# summarize layers
model.summary()

def plot_model_history(model_history):
    fig, axs = plt.subplots(1,2,figsize=(15,5))
    # summarize history for accuracy
    axs[0].plot(range(1,len(model_history.history['accuracy'])+1),model_history.history['accuracy'])
    axs[0].plot(range(1,len(model_history.history['val_accuracy'])+1),model_history.history['val_accuracy'])
    axs[0].set_title('Model Accuracy')
    axs[0].set_ylabel('Accuracy')
    axs[0].set_xlabel('Epoch')
    axs[0].set_xticks(np.arange(1,len(model_history.history['accuracy'])+1),len(model_history.history['accuracy'])/10)
    axs[0].legend(['train', 'val'], loc='best')
    # summarize history for loss
    axs[1].plot(range(1,len(model_history.history['loss'])+1),model_history.history['loss'])
    axs[1].plot(range(1,len(model_history.history['val_loss'])+1),model_history.history['val_loss'])
    axs[1].set_title('Model Loss')
    axs[1].set_ylabel('Loss')
    axs[1].set_xlabel('Epoch')
    axs[1].set_xticks(np.arange(1,len(model_history.history['loss'])+1),len(model_history.history['loss'])/10)
    axs[1].legend(['train', 'val'], loc='best')
    plt.show()
